segments.text: Then I'd have to go to class, so I'd drop it in this container.

Well, when the class was over and I went to the next class, I don't know how much space there might have been between classes, I'd get that cigar out and light it and smoke it until I got to the next class.
And sometimes I'd still be smoking that cigar, that same cigar at 12 o'clock, going to that 12 o'clock class.
It was pretty strong by that time.
But I was a regular cigar smoker.
But, of course, they smoked too many because I didn't have too much money.
Well, you'd make one of them last all day then.
Most of the day.
What about chewing?
Did a lot of the boys chew?
Yeah.
Yeah, they did.
But they had a hard time.
I think this will be an interesting incident.
One of the classes that I enjoyed going to was Dr. Mark Francis' class.
And sitting on this
particular classroom was a circular classroom with elevated seats.
And a boy from Miles Canale, he's down there, in the country where the Germans lived, you know.
And so we decided we'd play the trick on old Miles Canale, because he'd shoot in tobacco classes.
spit it out to one side, you know.
And we didn't pay attention to it particularly, despite the fact we didn't like it.
But Dr. Francis did.
And so we decided we'd fill every seat except one and leave one for Miles Connolly on the front row in front of Dr. Francis.
And so
when class started, and old Miles started chewing on this plug at the back up.
He didn't have any place to spit.
And he looked over to the right and looked over to the left, and finally had to get rid of it somehow.
So just whether it was right or left, I can't remember.
But anyhow.
Dr. Francis just got up and just like that went out of the room.
He was wondering what was happening.
And he came back with a five-gallon can, empty can, large can, and set it in front of Miles Canale and said, chew, and chew your head off.
And that big can, you know, he
That's the only experience we had about chewing tobacco in class.
You mentioned Dr. Francis, and I think you said you were very fond of him.
Was he one of your favorite teachers?
Yes, he was.
Who else were among your favorites?
John C. Burns, I guess, was my favorite, top favorite.
And then Dr. Francis.
I thought an awful lot of Dr. Francis because I had a lot of humor.
And he was just a good teacher.
Any others that you can think of?
Well, of course, I...
I think of some others that I didn't like so well.
Did you have any interesting experiences in chemistry?
I've talked to a number of people who weren't fond of the chemistry department.
Dr. Blake?
No, I didn't have any trouble.
I was good in chemistry, you see.
And I helped my roommate get through A&M by tutoring in chemistry.
He wasn't so hot in the sciences at all.
And then, of course, then I had Dr. Ball in Putney.
And I didn't particularly like Dr. Ball, but I didn't hate him, because he was always talking about when I was in Germany, we did so and so and so and so.
Now, in English, I forget just now who we had in English, but apparently he didn't make any favorable impression on me.
The only two was Burns and Francis, you see.
One thing that interested me, and I went through the yearbook,

1915 when you graduated and I jotted down the organizations that you belonged to and the things you did and I guess I sort of had one kind of picture of you and I was interviewing some of your other colleagues and they referred to you as Runt Stangle.
Right.
And how do you reconcile your size with your
great participation in intramural athletics.
You played a lot of football and baseball, I see.
Yeah, I did.
I don't know, but I played football the first year on the IK team.
I was too busy and finally decided I was just too busy to continue, so I quit.
So I didn't finish my season as a freshman.
As a sophomore, I played with I.K.
I believe, let's see, in 13 you were on the C.D.
That would have been your junior year, wouldn't it?
Yeah, we had a championship team in 13.
In 14, I was on the CD team.
And I was captain, I think, as well as I remember, of the CD team.
You also made the all-company football team as quarterback.
Yeah.
Was this a T-formation quarterback?
No, it's a little silver football.
That's what it is.
You got a silver football for being on the all-company team.
That was kind of the all-stars of the intramural.
But according to your book, you were quarterback of the team.
Right.
Did you then play T-formation?
That's where normally the quarterback played.
No, we played what we'd call a regular formation, mostly.
Now, this regular formation, you had a halfback here and a halfback here and a fullback here and a quarterback here in front.
Right behind the center.
Yeah.
And he'd pass this halfback or this halfback or this fullback would go through.
And there were times when he had a formation that we called eye formation.
And it just lined back straight up, one behind the other, you see.
That is, behind the line, you see.
Today they call the eye formation when the running backs line up behind the quarterback in an eye.
There were a number of other things I wanted to ask you about.
You seem to have been a member of a number of organizations.
One was the 466 Club.
Do you remember that at all?
No.
I was not a member of the 466 Club.
I was president of the Agricultural Scientific Association.
I don't know whether you got that down there or not.
Well, yeah, there's the president of the SAA, the Scientific Agriculture Association.
Yeah.
Do you have any recollection of what the 466 Club was?
No, I don't.
Okay.
What about the veterans of the Lost Cause?
No, I didn't, because, let's see, was that after the war or before the war?
Well, I don't know.
There were a number of people who were there around 14, 15, and 16 who were veterans of the lost cause.
And I have no idea what that was.
Was that possibly an organization of senior privates?
Now, senior privates.
Now, I'm familiar with the senior privates.
I was a member of the senior privates, yes.
Now, the senior privates was just
you might say a renegade outfit, you know, they didn't give them what they did, you know.
Weren't not particularly wild about the military.
And of course they were the ones that were not able to participate in the regular military events because of their jobs.
For instance, I had to be at the horse barn at 5 o'clock in the morning and then run over to the mess hall and get breakfast to get there to an 8 o'clock crash, you know.
Then I'd have to get there in the evening.
We're talking about the senior privates.
There's people who had jobs and therefore
couldn't really meet the regular military formations.
For instance, we'd drill between 12 and 1.
Eat a quick bite, you know, and get out there and drill.
Or sometimes not eat at all, you see.
And then, of course, we didn't have anywell, we had
uniforms as seniors, definitely designated as seniors.
Militarily, we didn't rate.
But I was recommended for an officer's rank by a lot of my friends.
But the man who was commandant named Brown didn't like me.
I've heard some people who had run in with Levi G. Brown.
Did they?
Well, I had.
I wanted to go someplace.
And he said, no, you can't go.
And I argued with him.
There wasn't any reason why I couldn't go.
And I went.
anyhow, you see, and that is the state affair.
That sort of puts you on his blacklist.

Yeah, I was on it, definitely on his blacklist, because when he came, when he was checking those who they were going to recommend for various officers for the following year, came across my name, mark right through it.
Okay.
I believe you also were in the Ross Volunteers.
Right.
So I was good enough to be in the Ross Volunteers, but not good enough to be an officer.
There were also mentioned in the yearbook that you were in the Newman Club.
Was that the Catholic men's organization as it is today?
And also the Press Club.
Yes.
I was an athletic sports writer, so I was on the press club, you see.
You wrote about the college athletics?
Right.
For what, the battalion or for other papers as well?
Mostly for the battalion.
Okay, and then you were also on the stock judging team for what, how many years?
One or two?
No, I was only one because the second year we didn't have a contest.
I don't know whether you know the background of that or not.
No.
But I was a member of the junior livestock judging team.
And as a member of the junior livestock judging team, I ranked for high place.
on that team was a fellow named Scott from McKinney, Texas.
He's dead, he's dead and gone now.
And then that is the junior, junior livestock judging team.
Now this junior livestock judging team competed in Fort Worth against teams from Oklahoma and Arkansas.
And we won the contest, you see.
And I, and I ran, and I,
And I didn't rank first, so I tied for first and split the money.
There was $75 that was first.
Well, since I wasn't first, we split $75 and $50.
And so that helped me a whole lot, because I sure needed the money.
Then we were getting ready for the international glass dog judging team.
developed foot and mouth disease in Mexico.
And they wanted to keep it out of the United States.
So they didn't take any chances.
rid of any animal that had been exposed to any animals near the Mexico border, you see.
And so they called off the International Livestock Judging Team just before to have been held.
So I didn't get to go to Chicago to the International Livestock Judging Contest.
And then would you be eligible for the stock judging team as a senior, or did they not have a team?
No.
We were through, you see.
When we competed as a junior and then getting ready to compete as a senior, when that yearwell, we were already packed ready to go.
So we didn't go, so we were through.
So I have, of course, the medal that they awarded to the senior members of the senior life.
When you graduated in the spring of 1915, did you have a job all lined up by the time you graduated, or did you have to hunt for one after that?
No.
I had a scholarship.
I had an opportunity to apply at the University of Missouri for an agricultural scholarship.
And so I received a $200 agricultural scholarship.
And so in September I went to Columbia, Missouri.
do graduate work, and that's what I did my first year.
Of course, I'll show you prices have soared.
I roomed with a fellow named Darnell, who had been and then came back as an instructor in the dairy department.
We ate in a place nearby.
Our room was $10 a month for the two of us.
And our meals were $5 for the week.
All you could eat.
$5 except Sunday.
You didn't get a Sunday evening meal.
And then that is it.

And now when I graduated there in June, and my first job was an instructor in animal husbandry at Texas A&M that John Burns gave me following a statement made by Dr. Bezal who was visiting on the University of Missouri campus.
campus when he asked me the question, Stangle, how would you like coming back to A&M?
I said, I sure would like it.
And that's what I did.
So you came back there then in the fall of 16.
And you stayed at A&M until when?
all the time in animal husbandry.
Did you have any particularly outstanding students that you could remember from that time period?
At A&M?
At A&M?
Yeah, I guess it was T. Burns, who was an outstanding student, Debbie T. Burns,
He's owned in Laredo or down there somewhere.
I forget now just where it is.
K.J.
Edwards was an outstanding student.
But of course the most outstanding student was my roommate, John Bugbee.
from Clarendon, Texas.
He was, let's see, what are our grades?
Anyhow, he was distinguished, that's right, distinguished every semester.
And then in, say, 25 you
took the job as head of the animal husbandry department at Texas Tech.
That was the first year they had classes here then.
Was that quite a step forward for you to move up as a department head even though it was a new school?
Yeah, it was.
And of course the person that was responsible for my coming here and taking the job was Dr. Francis.
And that's the reason I
rate him so high, because I didn't know what to do.
See, I was offered this position here, and I had to make a decision about coming here.
I'd visited here, and so I finally went to
No.
Proud of that.
The entire freshman class, not freshman, junior class, animal husbandry, that is junior animal husbandry students, came to my home and were on my porch begging me not to go to A&M.
I mean to Texas Tech, to stay at A&M.
So it was a hard decision to make.
and I had to make it by the next day.
So I'd go to this fellow and that fellow there, asking him what to do.
So it was Dr. Francis that made the decision for me.
When I asked him the question, should I stay here or should I go to Texas Tech,
He hesitated as he did in class many times, scratched his head, and then raised, I'd go.
And he says, if after 10 years you have only one bull and a barbed wire fence around that bull,
You know you've done it.
And I figured that is a challenge.
So I came here.
And of course, it was a challenge, because I didn't have a thing, except tumbleweeds, goat heads, and blue weeds, and so on, things like that.
It was really hard going.
And at what point was it that you were then elevated to dean of agriculture?
So 20 years as head of the department and then up to dean.
And you retired then in what?
1958 you retired.
And you've still been quite busy since then, though, haven't you?
Yes, I have.
Just the last few years, I've kind of slowed down, but I've been busy.
I took a big part in getting this cattle feeding started here.
I made four tours, planned four tours.
By cattle feeding, you mean the feedlot operations?
Feedlot operations, yeah.
When did you do that?
That was about early 1960s.
And I believe you've been, what, chairman of the board of directors of the National Farm Life Insurance Company.
Yes.
Were you involved with that organization before you retired?
Yes.
In fact, I'm still with it, you see.
Now, see, we started that in 1946.
So you were then one of the founders of the?
of this Farm Life Insurance Company?
National Farm Life Insurance.
National Farm Life.
And is that associated with the Agricultural Workers Mutual Auto Insurance?
Yes.
In other words, one helps the other.
In other words, a fellow will take out a policy and he may need
some insurance.
We find out that they needed some insurance, so we sell them some life insurance.
So the two companies work nicely together.
There are separate companies, though.
Separate companies, yes.
In the same building, of course.
Do the agents for the company sell both kinds of insurance, or do you have separate agents for it?
No.
We don't.
That's one thing.
We do not have any auto agents.
Uh-huh.
Just like...
In other words, if you want auto insurance with us, you have to apply.
Do you have to be a farm worker to get auto insurance with you?
You've got to be an agricultural worker, not a farm worker.
Yeah, agricultural worker.
I'm sorry.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Uh, you have to be an agricultural worker to have the farm life insurance, too?
No.
No?
Anybody can do it?
Anybody.
Were the two companies founded at the same time?
No, at the, uh, order one year later.
Uh-huh.
And you're still then associated with both of them?
Yeah, I am.
I'll let you have these.
OK. Now, you can have all of them.
I've got more of them.
All right, fine.
There was a couple of incidents that occurred while you were there, either probably while you were on the faculty that I thought I might ask you about.
One occurred in
early 1917, I believe, this would probably have been during your first year of teaching, when a group of boys from A&M went over to Austin and branded the steer.
Yeah.
Do you have any recollection of that incident?
Yeah, but I wasn't a part of it.
I realize you weren't a part of it.
You were on the faculty then.
Then about...
Three years later, as much as we can understand, that steer was butchered over in Austin, and they had a barbecue, and some people from A&M were invited.
We have had indication that this was the case from an unidentified clipping and from an invitation, but I haven't been able to find anybody who actually remembers that there actually was a barbecue.
Well, I don't remember a barbecue either.
Mm-hmm.
But you remember the branding incident?
Yes.
My assistant has talked with Hans Rohde, who wielded the branding on it.
Yeah, Hans Rohde, a great baseball player.
